Charles,<br><br>
Thanks for your enlightening point of view. You write as if this is a passion!<br><br>
I appreciate your elucidation of the paradidoxical nature of the Vietnam War, and your logic describing it. Like many paradoxes, there is usually never any specific correct resolution. I prefer to characterize the event as a vortex, an inward spiral from which none escape.<br><br>
If, as you say, that the behavior of those protesting is a paradox with the &quot;attributes&quot; of those involved, what, then, were the motives for the divergant activities. Clearly, something was not &quot;right&quot;. Do we need to look deeper than just at the political level? <br><br>
I am interested in the book of which you spoke. I know of no books &quot;banned&quot; in the United States, except those involving child pornography and the construction of thermonuclear devices. Although the Communists used such extreme population control techniques, in my view Hitler ranks high on the list. Remember, he was around for only a short time compared to the life cycle of communist regimes. His yearly quota was most likely on a par with Stalin.  
